Caption: Cuestas v. DiGiAnnounce
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
"I swear under penalty of perjury that I have a good faith belief that the material was removed or disabled by mistake or because of misidentification of the material."

Explanation of the Misrepresentation:

This statement is a misrepresentation because the material was not removed by mistake or misidentified. The listing in question was a derivative copy of my original, copyrighted pregnancy announcement. My work was created using real, physical props photographed in a 3D flat-lay scene, while the infringing design was generated using AI to replicate my composition, styling, and layout.

The infringer’s claim of a good faith belief is not supported by facts. She deliberately mimicked my design with slight alterations, resulting in a product that was clearly based on my original work. This is not a case of accidental use or misidentification—it was a willful and knowing infringement.

Her counter notice contains no explanation, evidence, or distinguishing features to support her claim that the removal was in error. The language used is a generic DMCA response, and in this case, it falsely represents the situation and attempts to justify unauthorized use of my copyrighted design. 
Additionally, I have reason to believe the address provided in the counter notice may be false or intentionally misleading. The counter notice lists a U.S. address in Jasper, Oregon (36763 Jasper Lowell Rd), but based on the nature of the account, activity patterns, and language used in the shop, I suspect the seller may be operating under a false identity or from a different location altogether.

Providing a false name or address in a DMCA counter notice is a serious misrepresentation and a violation of the DMCA's requirements for truthful disclosure. This further supports my claim that the counter notice was made in bad faith and that the infringing material should not be reinstated.
Relief sought:
The counter notice submitted by the infringing party contained a false statement of good faith belief that the material was removed in error. This misrepresentation caused additional stress, time, and financial burden on me as the original copyright holder.

Because of this counter notice, I am now forced to take legal action to prevent the infringing listing from being reinstated. This would not have been necessary if the infringer had not submitted a counter notice based on a knowingly false claim. Additionally, the infringer may have provided false or misleading contact information, which complicates proper legal service and further undermines the integrity of the DMCA process.
The misrepresentation also delays the enforcement of my copyright rights.

Relief Sought:
I am seeking:
A finding that the counter notice was submitted in bad faith and contained material misrepresentations.

Monetary damages to compensate for the time, costs, and harm incurred due to the misrepresentation.

A permanent order preventing the infringer from reposting the infringing material or submitting further fraudulent counter notices.

Caption: Pugh v. Brown
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
Brown’s statement that he had a "good faith belief" that my DMCA takedown request was mistaken or a misidentification is a misrepresentation because he knew, or should have known, that he had no legal right to use my copyrighted work, "Imma Let You Go," in his song "You Do You." I am the registered copyright owner of "Imma Let You Go" (Registration Number: SR 936-864, Effective Date: July 20, 2022), and a prior court hearing in Idaho (small claims case filed October 14, 2022) determined that Brown is not the original creator of the work. Additionally, DistroKid LLC issued a DMCA takedown notice (Request #7373092, dated October 24, 2022) to Brown, instructing him to remove all versions of "You Do You" from digital streaming platforms due to the infringement, and Brown refused to comply, leading DistroKid to remove the content.

Despite this clear evidence of infringement, Brown filed a counter-notification with SoundCloud, asserting a "good faith belief" that my takedown was mistaken, without claiming ownership of the copyright or providing any legal basis for his use of my work. This statement was knowingly false, as Brown was aware of the prior DistroKid’s takedown notice, both of which confirmed his lack of rights to my work. His misrepresentation caused material harm by leading SoundCloud to reinstate the infringing content after the 10-business-day window passed, allowing Brown to continue violating my copyright. This has resulted in potential lost revenue and licensing opportunities for my work, as well as the costs I’ve incurred to pursue this CCB claim (e.g., filing fees of $100 and time spent addressing the infringement). I request that the CCB award damages for this misrepresentation, in addition to the remedies sought for my copyright infringement claim.
Relief sought:
In 2025, Brown filed a counter-notification with SoundCloud (dispute ID# 108243967) that contained a false statement—namely, his assertion of a "good faith belief that the material was removed or disabled as a result of mistake or misidentification." Brown did not claim ownership of the copyright to "Imma Let You Go" or provide any legal basis (e.g., a license or fair use) for his use of my work, yet he filed the counter-notification, knowing he had no right to use my song. This misrepresentation led SoundCloud to reinstate the infringing content after the 10-business-day window passed, exacerbating the harm from the infringement:

Continued Infringement Due to Reinstatement: The reinstatement of "You Do You" on SoundCloud in 2025 allowed Brown to continue infringing on my copyright, adding to the financial harm already caused over the previous four years. This extended period of infringement, enabled by Brown’s false counter-notification, has further diluted the market for my work and caused additional lost revenue, which I estimate at $1,000–$2,000 for the period following the reinstatement (e.g., additional streams or exposure that Brown gained at my expense).
Costs of Pursuing This CCB Claim: Brown’s misrepresentation forced me to take additional legal action to protect my rights, including filing this CCB claim in 2025. I have incurred direct costs, such as the CCB filing fees ($100 total, with $40 paid initially and $60 due if the case becomes active), and potential service fees (estimated at $50–$100 if I need to hire a process server to serve Brown, as I do not have his address). Additionally, I have spent significant time preparing this claim, which I estimate at 10 hours. Valuing my time at a modest rate of $50 per hour, this amounts to $500 in lost productivity. These costs, totaling $650–$700, would not have been necessary if Brown had not filed a false counter-notification, as SoundCloud would have kept the content removed.
Emotional and Professional Burden: The need to pursue this CCB claim in 2025, after four years of dealing with Brown’s infringement, has added to the emotional and professional stress I’ve endured since 2021. I have been forced to divert even more time and resources from my creative work to address his ongoing infringement and misrepresentation, compounding the frustration and exhaustion caused by this prolonged ordeal.
In summary, Brown’s actions over four years (2021–2025) have caused me significant financial harm (lost revenue and licensing opportunities estimated at $11,000–$17,000), professional harm (damage to my reputation and artistic control), direct costs (CCB filing fees, time, and service fees totaling $650–$700), and emotional distress. The prior actions by DistroKid and other DSPs to remove Brown’s infringing content since 2022 demonstrate that his use is unauthorized, yet his persistence—enabled by the false counter-notification in 2025—has prolonged and exacerbated the harm to me.

Relief Sought
I seek the following relief from the CCB to address the harm caused by Brown’s copyright infringement and misrepresentation, totaling $29,000 in damages, which reflects the severe and prolonged impact of his actions over four years (2021–2025):

For the Copyright Infringement Claim:

Statutory Damages: I request statutory damages of $25,000 for the infringement of "Imma Let You Go." This amount is warranted due to the willful and prolonged nature of Brown’s infringement, which has persisted since 2021—four years of continuous violation of my copyright. Brown’s willfulness is evidenced by his refusal to comply with the DistroKid DMCA takedown notice (Request #7373092, dated October 24, 2022), the prior court determination in Idaho (small claims case filed October 14, 2022) that he is not the original creator, and his baseless counter-notification to SoundCloud in 2025 that did not claim ownership or provide any legal basis for his use. The CCB allows statutory damages of up to $15,000 per work for registered works, and I believe the maximum is appropriate given the duration and severity of the infringement. However, to fit within my total damages request of $29,000, I am allocating $25,000 to this claim, reflecting the significant financial, professional, and emotional harm caused over four years.
Cease Infringing Activity: I request that the CCB include in its determination a requirement that Brown cease distributing "You Do You" and any other releases that infringe on "Imma Let You Go" on all platforms, including SoundCloud, YouTube, TikTok, and others. I understand that the CCB cannot issue a binding injunction, but I seek this determination to prevent further harm to my intellectual property rights, with the expectation that Brown will agree to comply. A CCB determination of infringement will also enable me to request removal from other platforms through their DMCA processes, building on the precedent set by DistroKid and other DSPs that have already removed Brown’s infringing content since 2022. My ultimate goal is to ensure that all of Brown’s releases that infringe on my song are removed from all platforms, restoring my control over my work.
For the Misrepresentation Claim under the DMCA:

Damages for Costs Incurred: I request damages of $2,000 to cover the direct costs and additional harm caused by Brown’s false counter-notification in 2025, which led to the reinstatement of the infringing content and forced me to file this CCB claim. These costs include the CCB filing fees ($100 total), the estimated value of my time spent preparing this claim (10 hours at $50/hour, totaling $500), and potential service fees ($50–$100 to serve Brown, as I do not have his address). This totals $650–$700 in direct costs. Additionally, the reinstatement allowed Brown to continue infringing, causing further lost revenue, which I estimate at $1,300–$1,350 for the period following the reinstatement (e.g., additional streams or exposure Brown gained at my expense in 2025). Together, these amounts total $2,000, which I believe is a fair compensation for the harm caused by the misrepresentation.
Additional Damages for Prolonged Harm: The misrepresentation exacerbated the harm from the infringement by allowing Brown to continue his unauthorized use in 2025, adding to the four-year ordeal I’ve endured since 2021. This prolonged harm is reflected in the emotional and professional burden of having to pursue this claim, which I’ve factored into the damages for the infringement claim but also note here as a contributing factor to the overall impact of Brown’s actions.
Total Relief Sought: I seek total damages of $29,000, comprising $25,000 in statutory damages for the copyright infringement and $4,000 for the misrepresentation (covering my direct costs, lost revenue, and the additional harm caused by the reinstatement). The $29,000 reflects the cumulative impact of four years of infringement (2021–2025), the willful nature of Brown’s actions, and the exacerbation of harm caused by his false counter-notification in 2025. Additionally, I request a determination that Brown cease distributing "You Do You" and any other infringing releases on all platforms, to prevent further harm and allow me to fully enforce my rights across digital service providers.

Caption: Latkovic v. Amazon.com Services LLC, et al
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
1. Amazon’s Misrepresentation:

Amazon falsely claimed:
- "Third-party sellers are permitted to resell copies they have legally acquired."
- "We cannot remove these legitimate secondary market listings."

Misrepresentation Explanation:
Amazon failed to acknowledge that I have unpublished my books from Kindle Direct Publishing (KDP) and no longer authorize any sales. It is impossible for new copies to be entering circulation legitimately.
The listings falsely imply that these are still actively available books, misleading customers and damaging my control over my intellectual property.

2. Goodreads’ Misrepresentation:
Goodreads falsely claimed:
- "We do not remove listings of books that were once validly published."
Misrepresentation Explanation:
Goodreads presents itself as a book database, not a retail store, yet refuses to remove books even after their publication rights have been revoked.     This falsely implies my books are still in circulation, causing reputational harm. Goodreads is not a legal archive—they are actively choosing to keep infringing materials online against my explicit requests.

3. Google’s Misrepresentation:
Google falsely claimed:
- "We are unsure whether you are authorized to submit a copyright removal request."
Misrepresentation Explanation:
I provided official copyright registrations from the U.S. Copyright Office proving my ownership. I also provided metadata, screenshots, ISBN records, and takedown requests.

Despite overwhelming proof, Google refused to de-index the infringing pages, enabling continued exposure of my works.
Relief sought:
I have suffered financial, professional, and emotional harm due to these companies' refusal to honor my copyright takedown requests:

Financial Harm:
- Unauthorized third-party sellers on Amazon profit from my work while I receive nothing.
- Misleading listings misrepresent my publishing status, impacting potential future deals.

Reputational Harm:
- Goodreads and Google continue to associate me with outdated works, preventing me from moving forward under a new professional identity.
 - False listings damage credibility among potential publishers, agents, and industry professionals.

Emotional Distress & Legal Burden:
- The refusal to comply with basic DMCA procedures has caused weeks of frustration, requiring me to exhaust administrative and legal measures to protect my own work.
- The deliberate stonewalling and misrepresentations by these companies show a reckless disregard for copyright law.

Relief Sought:
- Immediate removal of Tycho Brahe Secret and Jung’s Demon from Amazon, Goodreads, and Google Search.
- Damages for financial and reputational harm caused by willful misrepresentation and refusal to comply with DMCA.
- An injunction preventing these companies from relisting or redistributing my works in the future without my explicit authorization.

Caption: Makulevskii v. Yuanping
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
The seller, VGYGLS, submitted a DMCA counter-notice that included the following false statement:
"I have a good faith belief that the material identified in the Notice of Infringement was removed or disabled as a result of mistake or misidentification of the material to be removed or disabled. I therefore request that the material be replaced and/or no longer disabled."
This statement constitutes a misrepresentation for the following reasons:
1.	Direct Copying of My Work
The infringing product listed by VGYGLS is an unauthorized reproduction of my original sculptural work. The infringer has copied key creative elements, including:
o	The stem has two bends identical to my original sculpture.
o	The relief of the leaves matches my work.
o	The bronze color, which is a distinctive and intentional artistic choice in my creation.
2.	Registered Copyright Ownership
I created this sculpture, and I hold the registered copyright (Attachment A) VA0002353500. This registration grants me the exclusive rights to reproduce, distribute, and display my work under Title 17, Chapter 1, § 102 of the United States Copyright Act.
3.	Violation of My Exclusive Rights
Under § 106 of the U.S. Copyright Act, I hold the exclusive rights to:
o	Reproduce my copyrighted work.
o	Create and distribute derivative works.
o	Publicly display and distribute copies of my sculpture.
The seller, VGYGLS, has unlawfully exercised these rights without authorization, falsely claiming non-infringement.
4.	Abuse of the DMCA Counter-Notice System
Under Title 2, § 512 of the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA):
o	VGYGLS knowingly made a false representation by claiming that the removal of the infringing material was due to a mistake or misidentification.
o	This constitutes an abuse of the DMCA notice-and-takedown process in an attempt to retain an infringing listing unlawfully.
5.	Harm and Statutory Damages
According to Chapter 5, § 504 of the U.S. Copyright Act, I am entitled to:
o	Statutory damages ranging from $750 to $30,000 per infringement, as determined by the court.
o	Compensation for the financial and reputational harm caused by the unauthorized use of my work.
Request for Immediate Action
Given this clear misrepresentation and copyright infringement, I request that:
1.	Amazon permanently removes the infringing listing and prevents its reinstatement.
2.	Amazon takes action against VGYGLS for abusing the DMCA counter-notice system and submitting a false statement.
3.	Amazon enforces stricter compliance measures to prevent future abuses of the DMCA process.
I appreciate your immediate attention to this matter and expect corrective action as soon as possible. Please confirm receipt of this complaint and provide an update on the actions Amazon will take to address this issue.
Relief sought: Injunction: A court order to cease the sale and distribution of the infringing works by the respondent.Monetary Compensation: Payment of $2,000 for the infringement of my copyright.Reimbursement of Legal Costs: Compensation for legal fees and expenses of $500 incurred in pursuing this claim.

Caption: Rabadanov v. Yao
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
"I have a good faith belief that the material identified in the Notice of Infringement was removed or disabled as a result of a mistake or misidentification of the material to be removed or disabled. I therefore request that the material be replaced and/or no longer disabled."

Chuangrong Yao under the brand BESZONE has been selling a copied sculpture on Amazon. The listing can be viewed at: https://www.amazon.com/Bronze-Anniversary-Year-Gifts-Everlasting/dp/B0CMZBKCNR/ref=sr_1_5?crid=1UMA2U67Z0UM&dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.CvyUXOBjEn_yRivnQq0QDg.DDpOS_kAvvQCw3gN9F4OvM1crN25JgEbWjPRxsM3yrg&dib_tag=se&keywords=B0CMZBKCNR&qid=1730480256&sprefix=b0cmzbkcnr,aps,244&sr=8-5
Our company is the original creator of this sculpture and holds a registered copyright. The infringing product replicates several distinctive creative elements of our work, including:
•	The form and positioning of the stem: The infringer's sculpture features a stem with two bends, mirroring our original design.
•	The rose leaves: The leaves in the infringer’s sculpture share the same shape and relief as ours.
•	The rosebud: The curvature and structure of the rosebud in the infringer’s sculpture are identical to our original creation.
•	The rose color: The infringer uses a bronze finish, which is a unique artistic choice in our work.
Timeline of Complaint Submissions and Amazon’s Responses
1.	January 8, 2025 – Our company discovered the infringing listing and submitted a complaint through the Amazon Infringement Reporting System.
2.	January 23, 2025 – Amazon notified us via email that the seller had submitted a counter-notice, implying that they did not admit to infringing our copyright.
To support our claim, we have attached:
•	Certificate of Copyright Registration VA0002417876 (Attachment A).
•	Photographic evidence of our original sculpture. (Attachment B).
Legal Basis for Copyright Infringement Under Title 17, Chapter 1, § 102 of the United States Copyright Act, pictorial, graphic, and sculptural works are legally protected.
Additionally, § 106 grants copyright owners exclusive rights, including:
•	The right to reproduce the copyrighted work.
•	The right to prepare derivative works based on the original.
BESZONE has violated these exclusive rights by copying our sculpture and distributing an unauthorized derivative version.
DMCA Violations and Misrepresentation by BESZONE
Under Title 2, § 512 of the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA):
•	BESZONE knowingly misrepresented that their product was not infringing when submitting a counter-notice.
•	The DMCA notice-and-takedown procedure was misused to retain the infringing listing on Amazon unlawfully.
Claim for Statutory Damages
According to Chapter 5, § 504 of the United States Copyright Act, our company is entitled to:
•	Statutory damages range from $750 to $30,000 per infringement, as determined by the court.
•	Compensation for the harm caused by this infringement, including financial losses and lack of proper attribution.
Additionally, the infringing brand BESZONE has misled consumers, falsely presenting the sculpture as their own. By unlawfully copying our work, they have:
•	Deprived us of rightful recognition and compensation.
•	Created an unauthorized derivative version of our work without our consent.
•	Misled Amazon through an unfair counter-notice submission.
Request for Immediate Action
Given this clear copyright violation, we request that Amazon:
1.	Immediately remove the infringing listing and prevent it from being reinstated.
2.	Enforce stricter measures to prevent abuse of the DMCA counter-notice system.
3.	Acknowledge our copyright ownership and implement actions to prevent further violations.
We appreciate your prompt attention to this matter and expect corrective action as soon as possible. Please confirm receipt of this complaint and provide an update regarding the actions Amazon will take to address the issue.
Relief sought:
Injunction: A court order to cease the sale and distribution of the infringing works by the respondent.
Monetary Compensation: Payment of $2,000 for the infringement of my copyright.
Reimbursement of Legal Costs: Compensation for legal fees and expenses of $500 incurred in pursuing this claim.

Caption: Kam, et al v. Ames, et al
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
The request of a copyright infringement notification for a video notice did not include a full legal name of the copyright owner, per the Youtube "Requirements for copyright infringement notifications: Videos"
Instead the  Respondent(requestor) used an old account name of "@ohnonora" that she does not have any legal rights to use, further the Respondent used an invalid email address where the alleged infringer(Claimant) has tried to contact her but email goes unanswered and rejected.
The Respondent sent the takedown notice based not on the particular charateristics of [the video] or any good-faith belief that it actually infringed a copyright but on its belief that, as 'a matter of principle'  that Respondent 'has the right to have her work removed.'
Furthermore the Respondent has never filed a registration application for a copyright of her work "SPTV SEASON FINALE", as described in her request of a copyright infringement notification for a video.

Per 17 U.S.C. Section 512(f) of the DMCA: DMCA rights holders need to consider “good faith” and common defenses to copyright infringement, such as “fair use” before sending the DMCA take down notice or they themselves can face their own legal challenges and a federal court lawsuit seeking damages and attorney's fees could be filed.
Relief sought:
HARM SUFFERED:
Upon the Claimant's video take down on YouTube the Respondent when live on YouTube to harass the Claimant and encouraged her 4.4K viewers to harass the Claimant and unsubscribe from the Claimant's channel of one quarter the amount of subscribers that the Respondent has.
The magnitude of the Respondent's online harassment and validation that YouTube provided her by removing the Claimant's video has caused the Claimant emotional distress, anxiety and a violation for her personal security due to the amount of personal threats being made to her by the Respondent's subscribers and channel members. Due to the emotional distress the Claimant who is a self employed artist had to cancel her upcoming events and commissioned art work
The Respondent has violated the Claimant's freedom of expression and opinion and caused the Claimant chilling of speech effects.
RELIEF BEING SOUGHT:
That the Respondent Retracts the copyright removal request
Reimburses the Claimant for the following:
(1) time and resources expended in dealing with the takedown notice;
(2) damages for reputational harm;
(3) damages for Claimant's emotional harm;
(4) damages for Claimant's chilled speech;
(5) costs and attorneys' fees incurred 
Claimant requests $4,960 for lost time, reputational harm, emotional distress, and chilled speech, $8,860 for lost time, costs of media relations, and reputational harm. Claimant also request $22,264 for attorneys' fees.  This district construes damages under § 512(f) broadly, as the statute's use of “any damage” in its language “suggests strong Congressional intent that recovery be available for damages even if they do not amount to substantial economic damages.” Lenz v. Universal Music Corp., No. 5:07–cv–03783–JF, 2013 WL 271673, at *9 (N.D.Cal. Jan. 24, 2013).
Also requesting that a criminal referral be made against Respondent for DMCA bullying in the copyright law context, along with violation of civil rights and the First Amendment: the Religion Clauses.

Caption: Body v. Llyod

I seek reimbursement for any legal fees or costs incurred as a result of pursuing this claim.

Caption: Late Night Crew LLC v. Torain
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
Words: "The respondent took the video from my YouTube channel (without permission) via a process called ripping the file." (Claim made with the CCB on 11/23/2024 at 4:22 PM EST).

Explanation: This statement is a misrepresentation because the claimant offers no evidence to support their claim about how I obtained the video. My video is not simply a re-upload of the claimant's video. It includes a substantial amount of original content, including a 20-minute introduction and monologue preceding any use of the claimant's material. This transformative use of the claimant's content contradicts their assertion that I merely "ripped the file."

2. Misrepresentation regarding the extent of copyrighted work used:

Words: "One hundred percent of my copyrighted work is being used in the reported video." (Claim made with the CCB on 11/23/2024 at 4:22 PM EST).

Explanation: This statement is demonstrably false. The claimant's own takedown notice contradicts this claim by specifying that the allegedly infringing content is limited to the timestamps of 0:26:55 – 0:44:50, totaling less than 20 minutes. Furthermore, the claimant's video is 2 hours long, while my video is 4 hours long. It is mathematically impossible for 100% of a 2-hour video to be contained within a 20-minute segment of a longer work.
Relief sought:
As a direct result of the false takedown notice, I suffered the following harm:

Financial Loss: The removal of my video resulted in a loss of ad revenue and potential new viewers. 
Reputational Harm: The false claim of copyright infringement damaged my reputation as a content creator within the YouTube community.
To remedy this harm, I request the following:

Statutory Damages: $5,000 to compensate for lost revenue, damage to reputation, and the time and effort spent addressing this false claim. This amount also covers any legal fees incurred.
Declaration of Misrepresentation: A formal declaration from the CCB stating that the takedown notice contained false information.
Retraction of the Notice: An order requiring the claimant to retract the false takedown notice.
Injunction: An injunction prohibiting the claimant from submitting further DMCA takedown notices against any content on my YouTube channel, including videos, live streams, community posts, and Shorts. This is necessary to prevent further harassment and disruption of my content creation activities.
I also request any other relief that the CCB deems just and proper in this matter.

Caption: Royale v. Smith
Explanation of the Misrepresentation: Zion Smith’s counter-notification is misleading and contains several inaccurate claims that distort the true nature of the dispute. While Zion asserts that we are in a legal dispute over the song’s royalties, the takedown notice was not for the entire song but was specifically filed for my verse, which comprised 1 minute and 55 seconds of the track. The DMCA takedown was solely focused on removing my copyrighted material, not the entire composition. Furthermore, Zion’s claim that we share equal rights to the song and that I am attempting to claim 100% of the royalties misrepresents the nature of our agreement and the actual issue at hand—my intellectual property and my right to control its use. The statement that we are currently in court over the song is misleading, as the ongoing legal proceedings are related to a restraining order, not the song’s copyright or royalty dispute. Additionally, Zion’s claim that she has documents to prove her position is vague and lacks specific evidence, further confusing the issue. Moreover, her assertion that I gave her consent to use my copyrighted material is false. I clearly communicated that I had withdrawn my participation and revoked any implied permission to use my work. Finally, the counter-notification’s claim that the takedown was a mistake is untrue, as the takedown notice was based on a legitimate and valid claim of copyright infringement. The content removed was exclusively my verse, and the purpose of my takedown was to protect my intellectual property rights.
Relief sought:
The counter-notification submitted by Zion Smith has caused significant harm to my reputation, my intellectual property rights, and my financial standing. By falsely claiming that I had granted her permission to use my copyrighted material and misrepresenting the nature of the dispute, Zion has perpetuated confusion and undermined my efforts to protect my work. Her claims that we are in a legal dispute over royalties are misleading and have distorted the true issue, which is the unauthorized use of my verse. This false narrative not only damages my professional image but also creates a misleading record of events that could affect future business relationships and opportunities.

Additionally, the counter-notification has resulted in ongoing harm by facilitating the reinstatement of the infringing content on YouTube. Despite my lawful takedown of the video, Zion’s actions, combined with the false counter-notification, have allowed the video to be restored, enabling her to continue profiting from my work without proper compensation or authorization. This ongoing infringement has resulted in a loss of potential revenue and opportunities that I would have rightfully earned had my intellectual property been respected.

Moreover, Zion’s actions have caused unnecessary financial strain. After she filed for a restraining order, which was ultimately denied by the court, I was forced to incur legal fees to defend myself against the baseless claims. The false restraining order not only resulted in unnecessary court costs but also delayed resolution of the infringement issue. As a result, I have been further financially burdened, facing both the costs of defending my rights and the continuing harm to my career and intellectual property.

Given the extent of the harm caused by these actions, I respectfully request the court to award statutory damages as provided under copyright law. These damages are necessary to compensate for the losses I have incurred, deter further infringements, and help recover the financial costs of defending my rights against the false claims made in the counter-notification and the restraining order.

Caption: Tate v. Crofton
Explanation of the Misrepresentation: I don't know the wording of the notices Aeronwen sent the online providers; however, the providers used words like "don't post things you don't have the rights to." Crofton is pushing the notion that I have no rights to post the music video we made together. I believe she is either not stating it was a collaboration with me or outright claiming I had nothing to do with it. I truly don't know the actual wording. I sense it's very simple without her going into any detail as to why.
Relief sought:
1. 9 months of work without pay with nothing to show, not even the ability to put it on my website. Work was lost because of it.
2. Months spent trying to understand if what Crofton was doing was legal or not —hiring a lawyer for legal advice.
3. YouTube demerit for copyright infringement.
4. It is difficult to convey how it feels to be utterly disrespected, to have my time, my years of experience, and my humanity dismissed.

I don't believe the CCB has the power to provide damages based on the lost work, lost time, and months of emotional stress, but it would certainly be nice to -- once and for all -- be granted the rights to something I worked my butt off for, a music video Lynn claims was made without her consent when, in fact, she was the driving force behind the collaboration from day one.

Caption: Nguyen v. Google LLC, D/B/A YouTube
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
The copyright owner failed to take into account the fair use exception to the copyright law.  
The principle law breaker in this case is actually YouTube, the service provider, who unilaterally and repeatedly chosen to not follow the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA) of 1998 - specifically Section 512(g)(1), which states: "...If the subscriber serves a counter notification complying with statutory requirements,....then unless the copyright owner files an action seeking a court order against the subscriber, the service provider must put the material back up within 10-14 business days after receiving the counter notification."
Relief sought:
My YouTube channel of over 5 years history with over 3000 subscribers (eligible for monetization) and growing rapidly was terminated by YouTube.  I lost all videos created.  I suffered emotional anguish due to this lost.  
I would like YouTube to follow the DMCA and cease and desist from rejecting validly filed counter notifications.  Only the court can determine if the alleged copyright infringement claim is valid when taking into account the fair use doctrine.  YouTube has no legal right to interfere with the law.

Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
I spent a great deal of time creating a logo for several shirts I wanted to create.  Each of these designs featured central components which were two circle/rings, with white spackle "grunge" texture.  Inside the rings, the title "Queen 399, Her Legend Lives On"

In my designs, I added  ©with my name; although I do realize that is not a legal, documented copyright, it is an implied copyright.  At the time I submitted my products to Etsy, I spent a great deal of time looking through all of the related pages, and there were no designs that looked like mine, hence my creativity.

A day or two after I submitted my listing and my product was visible on Etsy, I noticed a sticker/decal that used all of my design elements (the listing was newer than my listing - you can tell by the item number).  The double ring, the thickness of the rings, the saying, the years added, the title, the dual color silhouettes in the center.  The only thing that was changed was the font used for the title, but the font that was used was VERY similar to my work.

The only other thing they changed, is they covered my "middle" of the design with their own image, covering my implied copyright.  One can immediately see the similarities, and it is very, very similar to my work, and it was my idea.
Relief sought:
This has caused me a great deal of distress.  I created my logos/designs over several days, it took a great deal of time to come up with something not seen, different, and unique from other sellers.  In addition, after approaching her, she stated verbatim:
"I want to make it clear that my design is not copied from yours.  The circle outline used in my design is distinct, and my work clearly differs from yours in both execution and originality.  I ask you to refrain from making false accusations.  If you believe otherwise, I am confident that Etsy will recognize the individuality of my work?  (see attachment)

There is nothing "distinct" in her circle outlines; even the thickness of the lines are the same; the same grunge pattern was applied, and in the same color. 
There is nothing to note "difference in execution or originality" - her idea was not original, it was copied directly from mine.  It is clear my work directly inspired her copy.  The center "theme" is the same; silhouette w/ 2-3 colors.

It has greatly bothered me that I am also being called a liar; it has affected my current shop sales (all of my products featuring the same cause are donated to a charity), as well as future shop sales from those 3 designs I created and registered with Etsy.

I have also lost the integrity; the way people view my work is very important to me.  If people think that I copied someone else's work in an attempt to make a profit, that makes me look and feel dishonest   I have other designs in my shop that I did not create, I do not put my name on those.  Things I CREATE and I alone are the inspiration for, mean a lot to me.

Current sale, future sales, how people view my shops honesty and integrity are at stake.  I have also spent a lot of time documenting this, creating mockups for you to view, etc.

I am seeking damages, pay for my time, and any attorney fees I may accumulate.  Although I elected to represent myself, I will be hiring an attorney and have already contacted them.

Attached are examples of my design, the same design w/ copyright and name through them; my design has my name in the center of all of the circular designs.  I took the decal she made, and made an overlay with opacity at 37% so you can see my design under her own; you can see the dates match up exactly, the circles are almost identical as with the text and text placement.  The texture in the circles is the same affect.

I also attached a photo of her work; with the 4 designs offered using my design for the bulk of her represented work.  I am seeking $5000.00 in damages due to time, distress, attorney fee/advice, and loss of sales. If this ends up going further, and costing a lot more time, documentation, loss of sales and future sales, then I will proceed with small claims

Caption: Parsons v. Mannion
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
"aligns with fair use principles, providing critical commentary on an issue of public interest":  
A fictional drawing/map I, a private citizen, created in my personal and private Google Drive is NOT an issue of public interest.

"Purpose and Character of Use: The map was used for the purpose of commentary and critique, which is a transformative use" : 
It was not transformed.  It was simply put on screen in a video without my permission, without any context, without any proof of validity or relevance to the critique he thought was offered.  In fact, the commentary and critique provided was slanderous, harmful to my reputation & a total misrepresentation of a drawing that he had no right to share on a monetized video.

"My use was non-commercial and meant to provide insight on a matter of public interest":  
This Youtube channel is monetized, so any content published on it, by default, is commercial.  And again, my fictional drawings and creations are no matter of public interest, nor ever created for the purpose of being in the public sphere.

"Nature of the Copyrighted Work: The map is factual in nature": 
This 'map' is not at all factual in nature.  It was created by me for me & contains visual representations of my personal interpretation of hearsay, and was never going to be published by me or anyone else for any purpose.

"Amount and Substantiality: I used only a minimal portion of the map—about three seconds—" : 
It was, in fact, shown on screen for nearly THIRTY seconds along with the speaker stating "this is a map that [she] had drawn."  

"4. Effect on the Market: The use of the map in this context does not harm the market value of the original work,":
This is a ludicrous statement to make.
Relief sought:
The misrepresentation itself is considered harm.  Private citizens should not have to go through these processes to "prove" a drawing they made from their own independent thoughts, for their own personal use, are in fact their own. This YouTube creator has had many copyright claims filed on their channel & is a habitual offender.  The misrepresented counterclaim has taken up a substantial amount of my time to rectify, as well as time off of work.
But mostly, the grotesque mischaracterized "commentary" he claims he made about my personal work has caused extreme harm to my character and reputation. My drawing, that he had NO permission to share, was used for the purpose of "public interest" in the form of degradation, ridicule & encouraged brigaded harassment.

Caption: Robertson v. Smith
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
Misrepresentation Statements by Kimberly Smith:

1. "The content in question is entirely my original work."
2. "I am the sole creator and owner of the song, including the lyrics, composition, and production."
3. "The claimant has incorrectly identified my work as theirs."
4. "I have not used any unauthorized content from the claimant."



Kimberly Smith's statements are factually incorrect and intentionally misleading. In her live stream, she explicitly admitted that the content she was about to play, which included my copyrighted music, *Dani Montana (Instrumental)*, and my voice, was not her own. Despite this, she falsely claimed in the counter-notification that she is the creator and owner of the song. These statements misrepresent the true ownership of the work and were made with the intent to falsely assert her rights to circumvent the legitimate takedown of her video.

Her claim that I have incorrectly identified my work as hers is another falsehood, as it is registered under my name with the U.S. Copyright Office. Additionally, her statement that she has "not used any unauthorized content" from me is blatantly untrue, as she used my music and voice without permission, which constitutes unauthorized use under copyright law.

This misrepresentation seeks to avoid the consequences of her infringement by fraudulently claiming ownership over content that she neither created nor owns.
Relief sought:
Kimberly Smith’s unauthorized use of my copyrighted music, Dani Montana (Instrumental), and her false claims of ownership have caused significant harm both financially and to my reputation as a creator. By falsely claiming to own my registered work, she has been able to monetize my content on YouTube without my permission or any proper transformation under fair use. This has resulted in financial loss as she profits from my work, while I, the rightful copyright holder, am denied the revenue generated by her use of my content.

In addition to financial harm, her actions undermine my standing as the creator and owner of my copyrighted music. The fraudulent counter-notification submitted by Kimberly Smith circumvents the legitimate takedown processes intended to protect creators like me. This not only delays the rightful removal of infringing content but also sets a dangerous precedent where my intellectual property rights are openly challenged and devalued by false claims.

By continuing to claim my work as her own, Kimberly Smith is damaging my reputation within the creative community, diminishing my ability to control and protect my original content. Her actions also mislead her audience into believing that my work is hers, eroding the trust I have built with my own audience and potential collaborators. This deception causes ongoing harm to my brand and future opportunities.

Relief Sought:

I am seeking the following relief:

Monetary Compensation: Compensation in the amount of $1,500 for the financial loss incurred from Kimberly Smith’s unauthorized monetization of my work, including any revenue generated from YouTube based on the infringing content.

Penalties for Fraudulent Misrepresentation: I request that appropriate penalties be imposed on Kimberly Smith for submitting a fraudulent counter-notification under 17 U.S.C. § 512(f), which prohibits knowingly making material misrepresentations in a DMCA process.

Caption: Frazier v. Fierstien

In the counter notice, Mr. Fierstien claimed that I had identified his "For the People" design as infringing by mistake. Most likely he knew all along that there was no mistake and that he had finally been caught for his infringement.
Relief sought: As described above (in the section on infringement), I believe Mr. Fierstien's infringing products may have cost me thousands of dollars over the years. I do not know how much I lost, partly because I do not have a list of all the infringing product designs he sold, or how many of each design he sold. Mr. Fierstien's false counter notice to Etsy claiming that I made a mistake in identifying his "For the People" design as infringing, and his subsequent false report to Etsy that my "The Choice of Educated People" design was infringing on his "For the People" design should be factored into deciding the proper amount of relief. I ask the CCB to award me $5000 in relief for Mr. Fierstien's long-term, willful, ongoing and egregious conduct. Furthermore, I ask that Mr. Fierstien be ordered to cease offering his infringing "For the People" design on bumper stickers, bumper magnets, or any other products. He should also be ordered not to offer any other designs that substantively infringe on my "Choice of Educated People" design or any of my other similar designs. I would also like a declaration of non-infringement because the evidence clearly shows that my designs were the original designs pre-dating Fierstien's infringing designs by several years.

Caption: Jarman v. Hey Ricochet, et al
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
In this case, it's my opinion that both Shopify and Hey Ricochet had misrepresentations of my claim.
Shopify never removed the infringing content after I sent the DMCA takedown notice.
On 9/4/2024 they responded via email, stating:
"We’ve received your Digital Millennium Copyright Act takedown notice about heyricochet.com, but need more information before we can review. You can access the proper formatting, as well as additional information about our intellectual property policies here. 

We're unable to identify your original copyrighted work on the content on Shopify that you have reported. Please clarify which specific content (e.g. images, text) in the following link(s) you believe infringes your copyright: 

https://heyricochet.com/products/fairy-wings
https://heyricochet.com/collections/shop-all
https://heyricochet.com/

Shopify Trust & Safety

Ticket ID: ab3562dc-760f-4d3a-80d6-4d6a6557ae88"

I responded:
"Below are the links with explanation of the infringing work:
https://heyricochet.com/products/fairy-wings - this entire listing, the photos and product itself infringes on my copyright for Titania Fairy Wings because the wings on the comb are substantially similar to my work. Photos from the listing are attached.
https://heyricochet.com/collections/shop-all - the item called Fairy Wing Hair Combs infringes on my work as does the photo for that category
https://heyricochet.com/ - in the slideshow animation, the photo titled Fae Fantasy Collection. Screenshot attached.

I've also attached a side-by-side comparison named TitaniaHeyRicochetSideBySide showing the substantial similarity between my Titania fairy wings design and theirs, with only a couple veins removed. 
This specific wing design does not occur in nature, and furthermore, I've also made hair accessories and hair combs with my wing designs on them and planned to use this Titania Fairy Wings design this year. The use of such a substantially similar design by HeyRicochet harms my market to sell my own fairy wing hair combs.
I'm also attaching my copyright certificate."

Shopify responded on 9/6/2024:
"We're happy to help where we can, but we are unable to identify your copyright in the following link(s): 

https://heyricochet.com/products/fairy-wings
https://heyricochet.com/collections/shop-all
https://heyricochet.com/

Please reformat and resubmit your notice without the link(s) mentioned above."

I responded that I've provided all the evidence necessary and that they lose their Safe Harbor protections if the listing is not removed.

Then, today on 9/9/2024 they responded that a counter notice was filed:
"We have received a counter notice in response to the Digital Millennium Copyright Act takedown notice you submitted on 2024-09-01 23:04:50 UTC about heyricochet.com. 

In accordance with the provisions of the Digital Millennium Copyright Act, the removed content listed in the counter notice may be reposted, within 10-14 business days following receipt of the counter notice, unless Shopify receives notice that you have filed a legal action seeking a court order to restrain the merchant from engaging in infringing activity. 

Shopify Trust & Safety

Ticket ID: ab3562dc-760f-4d3a-80d6-4d6a6557ae88"

However, the content was never removed in the first place, so I'm not sure why a counter notice was filed.
I believe the infringing content is easily identified, and I provided all the necessary information, links, screenshots and a copy of my copyright certificate.
The counter notice states "I swear, under penalty of perjury, that I have a good faith belief that the affected content was removed as a result of a mistake or misidentification of the content to be removed."
However I don't believe there was any mistake or misidentification. 
I think it's clear that their product is substantially similar to my Titania Fairy Wings and therefore infringing.
Relief sought:
I've sent a Cease & Desist letter to Hey Ricochet on 8/26/2024, asking for the content to be removed within 28 hours, and hoped the issue could be settled privately and without the need to file a legal claim.
On August 29 I received an email response, saying:
"This letter serves to confirm receipt of your email re: Cease and Desist - Copyright Infringement on August 26th, 2024. We are working with counsel on a response to the claims put forth in the previously mentioned email and will respond in a reasonable time. 

Sincerely, 
Andrea Stein and Cayce Matteoli
Hey Ricochet, Inc. "

I've had no further response since beyond the counter notice, and the infringing item still has an active listing. As I stated earlier in this claim, the sales of the infringing fairy wing hair combs competes with my market and harms my ability to sell my own hair combs using my Titania Fairy Wings design. The price point is very low as the infringing work has been mass produced in China, which I believe is unfair competition when the design is a derivative of my own and I have not been paid a license fee or royalties.
I will wait until discovery to determine the damages I'm seeking.

Caption: Rucker v. Dillard, et al
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
The respondent,James Dillard, made a misrepresentation in all of his takedown notices and his counter-notices. The following are the words that made up the misrepresentation, YouTube asked the following questions to James Dillard and he gave them these answers: 

"How much of your copyrighted work is used? 2 Hours and 18 Minutes

How is the market for your original work affected by this use? It Diminishes the value of the original work since there is more than one copy in the same market. It reduces the effectiveness of future engagements with my subscribers by making them less interested in viewing the immediate release or live performance.

Does this use significantly transform your original work, or does it serve the same purpose? Same purpose, commentary as the original. They did not change the meaning in any way.

Does this use fall into an exception to copyright protection? No. Fair use does not cover this since the topic is the same.
They are using this only to defame my channel and reduce the effectiveness of the original content."

In all of his takedown notices he puts in the following legal language:

Country where copyright applies: US
I state UNDER PENALTY OF PERJURY that:
I am the owner, or an agent authorized to act on behalf of the owner of an exclusive right that is allegedly infringed.
I have a good faith belief that the use of the material in the manner complained of is not authorized by the copyright owner, its agent, or the law; and
This notification is accurate.
I acknowledge that under Section 512(f) of the DMCA any person who knowingly materially misrepresents that material or activity is infringing may be subject to liability for damages.
I understand that abuse of this tool will result in termination of my YouTube channel.
Authorized Signature: James Dillard

James Dillard used several different cyberbullying strategies in order to get all of my channels deleted from the YouTube platform. At first he used privacy notices and that didn't work. Because of his activities I was no longer able to earn revenue from YouTube. James Dillard is not only targeting me when it comes to the misrepresentation, he has targeted other content creators that have been critical with his content as well. He used the same abuse of copyright take down notices even though we have all won our own counter notifications against him but he keeps doing it. 

Due to his misrepresentation DMCA claims, I have been harmed for months. The relief I'm seeking would be the following:

1)A cease and desist from James Dillard. That means no more privacy notices, no more false claims for infringement through the copyright claims board, from YouTube, or any other social media platform. Not putting my name (legal name or alias name) on any legal documents. That includes his social media friends such as "Prism". Also a cease and desist from the use of any of my images, photos or content on all social media platforms. I will do the same as well, there will be no future content from me or any of my channels regarding him. I want the respondent, James Dillard to STOP making misrepresentations. That includes stop sending false takedown notices and counter-notices to me and other content creators that use fair use.

2)Having his claim for infringement, docket number #:23-CCB-0266, to be dismissed with prejudice so he can not file it again.

3)Preventing James Dillard from copyrighting his work with case#: 1-12843823841 with copyright.gov. He only created that case as a stalling strategy and to further harm me and the other content creators that used a screen shot photo of him as a thumbnail.

4)I'm seeking damages of $5,000. The amount includes filing fees, current legal representation, future legal representation, potential loss revenue from YouTube, my interest in freedom of expression, along with pain and suffering from not being able to defend myself against his false allegations.

5)To have James Dillard to drop both federal cases that contain my name. The cases will be attached to this claim. Also to drop any false cyberstalking reports, false TRO's, and any other police reports that contain my name.

6)Since the respondent has made videos degrading my reputation online, he needs to write a formal apology to the YouTube Legal & Copyright Department and suggest to them it was all a mistake and to have them restore ALL of my YouTube channels back as if nothing happened. There were no community violations that were done by Kenneth Rucker.

7)I would highly need the CCB staff attorneys to give me information about obtaining a subpoena under 17 USC 512 (h), which may help me obtain information from an online service provider to identify the other respondent on this claim, James Dillard's online friend that helped him create these false misrepresentation claims, "Prism". She specifically has been making online threats towards me and other content creators. The threats have been ongoing for months and it includes financial and physical. It's gotten so bad that I had to file a cybercrime report with the FBI and my local police department against both of them. James Dillard may have given her my contact information through the YouTube copyright counter notices that I sent and I'm concerned for my safety.

8)Because he has been abusing and violating the Digital Milliennium Copyright Act - 17 U.S.C. 512(f) DMCA law, James Dillard needs to be permanently removed from the YouTube platform.

Caption: Hill v. Aichwalder
Explanation of the Misrepresentation: I swear under penalty of perjury that I have a good faith belief that the material was removed or disabled by mistake or because of misidentification of the material.
Relief sought:
To begin I must state that the particular copyright work (Soccer Skeleton Overhead Kick Soccer Player Halloween Moon) that is the subject of this proceeding was intended to be available (offered for sale) solely through my own sales account located on the Amazon.com Merch on Demand marketplace platform. The copyright work was uploaded by me to the Amazon.com Merch on Demand platform to be sold only as a design printed on physical products such as shirts, tote bags, hoodies, etc. No digital download of this product is or was offered nor any authorized by myself or Amazon.com. The only method anyone can legally obtain this copyright work is through the purchase of products offered by Amazon.com that include the design printed on it. All other uses are unauthorized.

The activity of Erica Aichwalder has contributed to a loss of sales revenue that is incalculable due to the nature of this type of copyright infringement. The respondent somehow obtained an unauthorized copy of my copyright work and created a listing on etsy.com which offered it for sale to the public as a digital download in the form of a PNG file with transparent background. 

The Respondents listing title included the phrase "Soccer Skeleton Overhead Kick Soccer Player Halloween Moon, Png For Shirt, Png Files For Sublimation, Digital Download, Printable" which mislead all buyers to believe that Erica Aichwalder had the rights to resell my copyright work and that they, the buyer, were also being given the right to use and resell my copyright work on products such as T-shirts and other items that the design could be printed on. 

The respondent's activity has helped to distribute my copyright work without my permission to an unknown quantity of people, both within and outside the United States, that in turn may and most likely have created products which compete with my own listings located on the Amazon.com marketplace. This includes but is not limited to using my unauthorized copyright work to sell products not only on other platforms such as a private ecommerce website, etsy.com, teepublic.com, redbubble.com, zazzle.com but also Amazon.com as well which directly competes with my own original listings created with my own copyright work. 

The respondent's activity has directly contributed to and increased the unauthorized use and spread of my copyright work both within and outside the United States. The result is that my ability to sell and profit from my own copyright work has been diminished significantly.   

In fact I have had to issue numerous takedown requests since listing my copyright work on the Amazon.com marketplace and I have no doubt that some may be the result of Erica Aichwalder's activity which allowed people to purchase an unauthorized hi-resolution copy of my copyright work for a mere $1.20

This not only harms me financially but contributes to my mental stress as well as adding extra work load to my schedule which I do not get paid for. Rather than using my time to create designs I am forced to waste my time tracking down unauthorized copies of my work and trying to protect it from those like the respondent who deem that theft is okay.

Caption: van Niekerk v. TMG | Trident Media Guard
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
Misrepresentation 1: "I state UNDER PENALTY OF PERJURY that:
I am the owner, or an agent authorized to act on behalf of the owner of an exclusive right that is allegedly infringed. I have a good faith belief that the use of the material in the manner complained of is not authorized by the copyright owner, its agent, or the law; and This notification is accurate. I acknowledge that under Section 512(f) of the DMCA any person who knowingly materially misrepresents that material or activity is infringing may be subject to liability for damages. I understand that abuse of this tool will result in termination of my YouTube channel. 
Authorized Signature: Bastien Casalta"

Reason for Misrepresentation 1:
In response to the takedown notice issued by TMG, represented by Mr. Bastien Casalta, I wish to assert that this notice presents a fundamental misrepresentation regarding the nature of my videos and their relation to copyright law, particularly the "fair use" provisions.

Mr. Casalta's notice states "UNDER PENALTY OF PERJURY" that he believes my use of the material "is not authorized by the copyright owner, its agent, or the law." I contend that this assessment is fundamentally flawed for the following reasons:

Purpose and Character of Use: My videos aren't replicas or mere reproductions of the original rugby matches. They undergo considerable transformation. Using CoachPaint, I edit, annotate, and introduce graphical effects to illuminate rugby laws' intricacies. This transformative use, accompanied by my educational commentary, establishes a different purpose from the original broadcasts.

Nature of the Copyrighted Work: The original rugby matches, while copyrighted, serve a distinct purpose from my videos. My videos are analytical and educational, not replays. They provide a comprehensive view of specific game aspects, underscoring the essence of fair use.

Amount and Substantiality of the Portion Used: I employ only selected segments of the game, representing a tiny fraction of the entire content. Out of 2,000-3,000 rugby events in a game, my focus is on just 10-25. This selective use emphasizes the educational aspect, differing starkly from the original broadcast's intent.

Effect on the Market: My videos address a unique niche, focusing on refereeing analysis—a perspective barely covered on platforms like YouTube. They neither substitute nor detract from the original broadcasts but foster a deeper appreciation of the game.

Mr. Casalta's declaration, asserting that my content's use "is not authorized by the law," seems to dismiss the well-established provisions of "fair use" within copyright law. The law explicitly allows for transformative, educational use like mine.

Given the tenets of fair use and the unique nature of my content, TMG's claim appears to be a misrepresentation. I would like to remind the you of Section 512(f) of the DMCA, which Mr. Casalta referenced: any person who "knowingly materially misrepresents that material or activity is infringing may be subject to liability for damages." I believe my videos squarely fall within fair use, and TMG's takedown notice, in failing to recognize this, has done a disservice to the broader rugby community and YouTube's platform.
Relief sought:
I would like to highlight the extensive repercussions and losses that I, as a dedicated and hardworking content creator, have faced due to World Rugby's undue actions.

Projected Revenue Loss: The World Cup represents a significant influx in viewership for rugby-related content. Using a single video as a benchmark that garnered 230k views and generated $900 in a short span, and juxtaposing it against my historic channel metrics, I was poised to make around $1,500 for this one video alone. Had I been able to post the 8 videos that were planned for the duration of the World Cup, with a conservative estimate of $500 each in revenue, the projected earnings would have been $4,000. This amount excludes potential revenue from increased sponsorships and partnerships, which are commonplace during such high-profile events.

Opportunity Cost: The World Cup is a quadrennial event, which means lost opportunities during this period are not recoverable until four years later. This is not just a month of lost revenue; it's a loss of four years' worth of specialized content capitalization.

Algorithmic Penalization: YouTube's algorithm is intricate. With these unjust strikes, my channel has faced a significant algorithmic setback, seeing a 60-80% drop in views on older videos. Given the way YouTube operates, regaining this lost ground is not just about waiting for the strikes to be removed; it can take months, even years, to reestablish a channel's standing.

Loss of Potential Subscribers: Considering the heightened interest in rugby during the World Cup, my channel's growth was stunted at a crucial juncture. Given the ripple effect of every subscriber bringing in more through word of mouth, shares, and recommendations, the loss isn't just of the immediate subscribers, but of the potential exponential growth I was poised to experience.

Reputation and Trust Damage: Trust, once lost, is hard to regain. The perceived legitimacy of my content has been questioned due to these takedowns, affecting not only viewer trust but also potential collaborations, sponsorships, and partnership opportunities. This loss, although intangible, has long-term repercussions on my earning potential and credibility.

Emotional and Mental Distress: Beyond the financial and reputational losses, the stress and emotional turmoil caused by this ordeal shouldn't be understated. I've invested time, effort, and passion into my channel, and to see it unjustly penalized takes a toll on my well-being.

Given the depth and breadth of the damages and losses sustained, a claim of $30,000 isn't arbitrary or capricious. It's a justified compensation for the multifaceted negative impacts I've been subjected to. Beyond this monetary claim, I reiterate the need for a public apology from World Rugby and the immediate removal of these baseless strikes against my channel and abstain from repeatedly targeting my content with baseless claims that show a blatant disregard for the principles of Fair Use and copyright laws.

Caption: Keel v. Fuirk Home, LLC
Explanation of the Misrepresentation:
Copy of counter notice attached. The specific claim made in the counternotice was "I swear, under penalty of perjury, that I have a good faith belief that the affected material was removed or disabled as a result of a mistake or misidentification of the material to be removed or disabled and that I am the merchant subject to the DMCA Takedown Notice
referred to above or I am authorised to act on behalf of that merchant."
I initially correspondend with the respondent on 8/6/23 via Facebook and Facebook Messanger, the day that I became aware of the copyright infringement. Copies of all correspondence are included as supplemental documents. In our initial communication, I asked the respondent to take down the image or add attribution. The respondent agreed to add attribution to remedy the unauthorized use of the image, and indicated that would be completed by 8/9/23. The initial DMCA takedown notice was sent on 8/14/23, when several days had elapsed since the 8/9 date the respondent had provided, with no communication from the respondent that they needed additional time and continued promotion of the website with the infringing image posted. After the infrining content was initially taken offline on 8/15, the respondent contacted me by email asking for the violation request to be removed, suggesting that she had fulfilled the condition of adding attribution by adding a "link" and saying that she would take down the photo if the "link" was not acceptable. When I had checked the website on 8/15, several hours before I received confirmation that the infringing content was taken down, there was no "link" or attribution accompanying the image. I indicated in my email response in part that based on her actions up to that point, she needed to find a different image to use for that product listing. The full response is included in the copies of the correspondence, but she said in part "I'm happy to do that...I understand your rights and your concerns." 

Several days later I saw that the URL's that were taken down by Shopify were restored, my content was gone, and I expected that was the end of it, and I had no intention of pursing it further. On 9/2/23 I was scrolling through Facebook and saw a sponsored post for the respondent's website. I clicked on it and saw that the listing and my photograph were back on the site, and there was no attempt to provide attribution for the image in the listing. I sent a second DMCA takedown request to Shopify on 9/2/23 and received notification from Shopify on 9/5 that the content listed as infringing in the original Takedown Notice had been taken offline. About one hour later I received notifcation from Shopfiy that the the respondent had responded to the DMCA Takedown Notice with a Counter Notice, indicating that the content was taken down as the result of a mistake or misidentification of the work. The email indicates that the material may be replaced and access no longer disabled within 10-14 days unless Shopify receives notice that I have filed an action against the Merchant. At this point the infringing image is not posted, but the 10-14 business days has not yet elapsed. 

Based on my communication via Facebook and email with the respondent prior to sending the second takedown notice, the respondent made a misrepresentation in filing the counter claim, and knew that the misrepresentation was false, because they had already acknowledged that I am the copyright owner, acknowledged that they used the image withouth permission, and had agreed to discontinue use of the image after they failed to add attribution in a timely manner. Even though the respondent claims that they did add a "link" as attribution prior to the content being taken down the first time, I did not ever see evidence attribution was added, and screen capture video and images of the website after the repost show that there was no attribution for the image, so it is not possible that this is a miscommunication about attribution.
Relief sought: I am seeking damages for the harm caused by the misrepresentation. When I became aware of the copyright infringement I immediately notified the respondent but offered the respondent continued use the image contingent on attribution being added, which would have allowed the unauthorized use to be quickly and simply resolved for both parties. Instead of just adding image attribution to the written description for the listing, the respondent chose to continue to use the image without authorization, and then to further escalate the unauthorized use by making false statements in the counter-notice they filed, which will result in their ability to repost the image as a listing photo on their site. Ranunculus corms are typically shipped in the fall in the United States, and although they are dormant, are a perishable product. As a result of the second DMCA takedown, the specific listing using the work is not active on the website, which means that customers are not able to order the inventory the respondent has purchased. Without taking additional legal steps against the respondent, the misrepresentation in the counter claim will allow the respondent to have this listing with the photo active again, and continue to profit off the unauthorized use of my work.
